<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-380-992  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 380 992.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  June 26 1989 v8 n13 p4(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Army interested in Navy contract for super-minis.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>An official of the Army's Small Computer Programs (SCP)headquarters confirms that the service is interested in procuringup to 1,500 super-minicomputers via the Navy's super-mini umbrellaprogram.andP;  In early Jun 1989, the Navy shifted to a joint servicesapproach to launch the super-mini program.andP;  Navy acquisitionsrepresentatives met with Air Force Computer Acquisitions Center(AFCAC) representatives to discuss making AFCAC responsible forthe procurement.andP;  The Army official says the SCP'ssuper-minicomputer requirements may be greater than the Navy's andthat the computers would be deployed throughout its installationsand commands.andP;  Sources at all three services believe a jointacquisition of super-minicomputers would lower costs and offermulti-service compatibility.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. NavyGovernment ContractsUnited States. ArmyMinicomputersAcquisition.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Army Interested In Navy Contract For Super-MinisandM;An Army official has confirmed that the service is interested in procuringsuper-minicomputers through the Navy's fledgling super-mini umbrella program,a buy that might soar to $500 million.andM;Lt.andP;  col.andP;  Richard T. Fraser, a product manager of the Army's Small ComputerPrograms (SCP) headquarters at Fort Monmouth, N.J., said, &quot;There is Armyinterest in the Navy super-mini umbrella program.&quot;andM;Fraser confirmed that the Army might buy as many as 1,500 machines throughthe acquisition.andM;Earlier this month, Navy officials said they had shifted to a joint servicesapproach in their year-old effort to launch the super-mini program.andP;  In lateMay, Navy acquisitions representatives met with representatives of the AirForce Computer Acquisitions Center at Hanscom Air Force Base, Mass., todiscuss making AFCAC responsible for the procurement [GCN, June 12].andM;Fraser said the Army would deploy the super-minis throughout itsinstallations and commands.andP;  &quot;Our requirement is for something with greatercapacity than what is known as the small multiuser computer, which is a16-user network,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;We have areas where we need up to 256-usernetworks.&quot;andM;Although no Army personnel were involved in the meeting at AFCAC, Fraser saidSCP officials have been in contact with Navy procurement managers.andP;  &quot;I'd saythere's a strong possibility we'll pitch in with them,&quot; he said.andM;Some DivergenceandM;Fraser said SCP had a few requirements that went beyond the Navy's, including&quot;some local area network items, our required Ada compilers and just a fewthings we need to make sure the super-mini can talk to our existingarchitecture.&quot;andM;He said Army technical staff at the Fort Huachuca, Ariz., headquarters of theInformation Systems Engineering Command first reviewed the Navy's preliminaryspecifications for the buy about three months ago.andM;A month later, the services first met to talk about the super-mini program,he said.andM;The draft specifications for the purchase call for systems that support 64,128 and 256 concurrent users.andM;Fraser said he thought about 40 percent of the Army's 1,500 machines would be256-user systems.andM;Sources at all three services agreed that a joint acquisition of super-minisoffers advantages that include lower costs and multiservice compatibility.andM;Fraser pointed to the joint purchase of Zenith Data Systems Corp.'s Z-248micro-computer through the Desktop II procurement several years ago as anexample that ought to be emulated whenever possible.andP;  &quot;That really worked outwell for everyone,&quot; he said.andO;</TEXT></DOC>